      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Selling a House With Asbestos in Brisbane: What Sellers Must Know
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        Most Brisbane homes built before 1990 contain asbestos somewhere. Here is what sellers need to know about disclosure, the bonded versus friable distinction, finance implications, and what it actually means for your sale price.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>If your Brisbane home was built before 1990, the presence of asbestos-containing materials somewhere in the structure is more likely than not. Australia was one of the world's largest consumers of asbestos products per capita through the mid-twentieth century, and Queensland's housing stock reflects that. Fibro sheeting, eave lining, bathroom wet area lining, floor tiles, roof sheeting, and internal wall linings in homes built between the 1940s and the mid-1980s frequently contain asbestos. For sellers, the question is not usually whether asbestos is present, but what type it is, whether it is in good condition, and how to handle it through a sales campaign without it becoming a distraction or a negotiation lever for buyers.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Bonded versus friable: the distinction that matters most</h2>
      <p>Not all asbestos is the same. The critical distinction for sellers is between bonded (non-friable) and friable asbestos. Bonded asbestos is asbestos mixed with a binding material, typically cement, and formed into a solid product. Fibro sheeting, compressed cement eave lining, and floor tiles with asbestos content are typically bonded materials. When bonded asbestos is intact and in good condition, with no breakage, drilling, sanding, or deterioration, it poses minimal risk. The fibres are locked into the matrix and cannot become airborne under normal conditions.</p>

      <p>Friable asbestos is material where the asbestos fibres are loosely bound or have deteriorated to a point where they can be crumbled, pulverised, or reduced to powder by hand pressure. Friable asbestos is the serious category. Old pipe lagging, roof insulation products, and spray-applied fireproofing can contain friable asbestos. This category requires licensed removal and carries more weight in a sale context because of the remediation obligations and the financing implications discussed below.</p>

      <p>Bonded asbestos that is undamaged and identified is manageable in a sales campaign. Friable asbestos requires professional assessment and often professional removal before or concurrent with sale. The practical advice for sellers: if you are unsure which category applies, get an asbestos assessment done before you list, not after a buyer raises it as a condition.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Disclosure obligations in Queensland</h2>
      <p>Queensland does not have a specific statutory requirement to declare known asbestos in a residential property disclosure statement in the same way pool safety and smoke alarm compliance are required. However, the general obligations under the Property Occupations Act and Australian Consumer Law mean that sellers and agents cannot mislead buyers by omission of a material fact. If you know asbestos is present and do not disclose it, a buyer who discovers it after contract can have grounds to claim they were misled.</p>

      <p>The practical standard, and the one that protects sellers most effectively, is proactive disclosure with documentation. An asbestos register prepared by a licensed asbestos assessor, provided to buyers as part of the contract documentation, removes ambiguity. It shows you know what is there, you have had it assessed professionally, and you are being transparent. That approach tends to reduce the negotiating leverage asbestos gives buyers compared to a situation where they find it themselves through a building inspection and bring it to the table as an undisclosed defect.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Agent obligations</h2>
      <p>Under the Property Occupations Act 2014, real estate agents are required to disclose all relevant facts about a property that could reasonably be expected to influence a buyer's decision. An agent who knows a property contains asbestos and does not disclose it is potentially in breach of their obligations. In practice, most experienced agents in Brisbane's inner east are accustomed to managing asbestos disclosure as a standard part of the pre-listing process for older homes. An agent who is uncomfortable discussing it or who suggests you say nothing is not giving you sound advice.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Impact on buyer pool and finance</h2>
      <p>Bonded asbestos in good condition in a Brisbane inner east home does not materially reduce the buyer pool for that type of property. Buyers purchasing older Queenslanders, interwar homes, and postwar fibro homes in suburbs like Morningside, Coorparoo, Cannon Hill, and Hawthorne understand the context. Many are purchasing specifically to renovate, and they factor asbestos management into their renovation budget as a known cost rather than a shock.</p>

      <p>Finance approval is a different question. Most major lenders will not refuse finance on a property because bonded asbestos is present and documented. What can create financing complications is friable asbestos with no remediation plan, or a valuer noting significant unmanaged asbestos risk in a valuation report. Buyers using certain loan products, including some construction loans and low-deposit loans with mortgage insurance, may face additional scrutiny. The cleaner approach for sellers is to either remediate or obtain a clear asbestos register before listing, so the documentation supports rather than complicates the buyer's financing.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Does asbestos have to be removed before sale?</h2>
      <p>For bonded asbestos in good condition, removal before sale is not required under Queensland law. The obligation to remove asbestos arises when the material is disturbed, deteriorating, or in a location where ongoing deterioration is likely. A property sold with intact bonded asbestos simply transfers the management responsibility to the new owner, who is then subject to WorkSafe Queensland requirements when renovating or demolishing.</p>

      <p>Sellers who are considering removal as a pre-sale strategy should think carefully about the cost-benefit. Asbestos removal in a Brisbane home is a specialist job requiring licensed removalists and disposal in approved facilities. Removing all asbestos from a fibro home built in the 1950s is a major undertaking, often costing tens of thousands of dollars. For most inner east properties, the sale price premium from complete removal does not recover the removal cost, particularly since buyers already expect and price in asbestos in that era of home. The exception is a property where asbestos in a visible, high-traffic area (such as a bathroom wet area with damaged fibro) is likely to cause buyers to walk away or discount heavily.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Getting an asbestos register</h2>
      <p>An asbestos register is a document produced by a licensed asbestos assessor after a visual inspection of the property. It identifies the location, condition, and type of asbestos-containing materials found. For residential properties, this is typically a straightforward inspection costing a few hundred dollars. The register tells buyers exactly what they are dealing with, which is far more useful and far less alarming than a building inspection report that simply flags suspected asbestos throughout without detail.</p>

      <p>Once you have a register, you and your agent can provide it to buyers as a factual document. Buyers who are seriously considering the property can review it with their own asbestos assessor or contractor before making an offer. This normalises the asbestos conversation and prevents it from becoming a late-campaign negotiation point after a building inspection.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Realistic impact on sale price</h2>
      <p>For a typical Brisbane inner east home from the pre-1990 era, disclosed and documented bonded asbestos in good condition has minimal impact on sale price relative to comparable properties. It is expected. Where asbestos does affect price is when it is undisclosed, discovered by buyers late in the campaign, or when it involves friable material requiring significant remediation. In those situations, buyers factor in remediation costs, the uncertainty, and the negotiating opportunity all at once, which consistently produces worse outcomes than proactive disclosure would have.</p>

      <p>The pattern in well-managed sales is clear: sellers who commission an asbestos register before listing, provide it as part of their contract documentation, and brief their agent to discuss it openly with prospective buyers, consistently achieve better results than sellers who try to avoid the conversation. Transparency does not reduce your price when the buyers already expect the issue to be there. Concealment and late discovery does.</p>

